Upon arriving at the delivery location, consignee found 1 box was wet. Consignee opened box and found 1 of the 20 containers inside leaking. Appears leak was noticed by shipper who put absorbant material inside of box and closed it and loaded it onto a vehicle for transport.  Consignee reloaded box onto our vehicle and refused container. FCC contacted SWS in the Atlanta area to meet our driver at the consignee's location, wiped residue off 19 uncompromised containers and removed the 1 leaking container. Consignee agreed to accept the remaining 19 containers.
column169: Shippers should be held accountable for knowingly putting a leaking container into the transportation system

column168: No apparent release to environment seems to be confined to aft cargo compartment only. GRD ID 26142 - MENZIES AVIATION - Ramp  On inbound flight AS399 Zone manager Mitch was down loading the AFT cargo pit when he noticed silver balls inside of every other widget in the pit floor and thought they were balls from a necklace and touched it with his finger with gloves on and it rolled and had a liquid form to it so he called MTX to come inspect it and turned out to be mercury. The outbound flight was swapped to a different A/C and A/C 471 was towed to the hanger for further inspection.  At this time the aircraft is under assessment and no cause or source has been determined.  The figures for the amounts are estimated/damage estimated. Cleanscapes environmental estimates the amount vacuumed up by a mercury vacuum to be the "size of a marble" thus the 10 gram estimated amount.

column168: At approximately 1830 on 11/12/15 the driver picked up trailer 6405 at Spring Grove, Ohio. After securing the rear of the load the driver took a 10 hour break. At approximately 0445 the driver conducted his pre-trip inspection and tire check and began his trip. At approximately 0630 the driver stopped at the TA Truck Stop in London, Ohio to have a suspension adjustment made. As the driver was preparing to enter the shop he noticed liquid leaking from the trailer near the landing gear. The driver immediately moved the vehicle to a safe location, placed a bucket under the trailer to contain the leak and notified his manager who advised him to notify the truck stop, local police and fire departments. Upon arrival the local police and fire departments checked the manifests and established a 300 foot perimeter around the vehicle. Approximately one hour later personnel from the Ohio Highway patrol Haz Mat unit entered the trailer to establish which drum was leaking. They identified a drum near the front of the trailer as having a pin hole in the side. Upon the notification from the Haz Mat team the driver secured the trailer and waited for the Clean Harbors Emergency response Team to arrive.  At 0700 on 11/13/15, a Clean Harbors Emergency Response Team was dispatched from Cincinnati, Ohio to remediate the spill. The team reviewed the load information with Clean Harbors Environmental Health and Safety to establish the proper equipment necessary for this response and was enroute at 0845. The Emergency response team arrived at 1015 and met with the driver and Ohio Highway Patrol Haz Mat team to determine the location of the leaking drum and checked the drum against the manifest. At 1145, after setting up Air and Confined Space Entry equipment the response team donned appropriate Personal Protective equipment and entered the trailer and plugged the leaking drum. At 1230 they laid down clay absorbent and packed it around the drum at the direction of the Ohio Highway Patrol Haz Mat Team leader. At 1345 the Emergency Response Team re-secured the trailer and load, cleaned up the absorbents from the ground and wiped down the frame rails and underside of the trailer. At 1430 they demobed from the site and followed the driver back to Spring Grove, Ohio at the direction of the State Haz Mat Patrolmen. At 1630 the driver and response team arrived at Spring Grove, Ohio where the trailer was placed in containment and turned over to plant personnel.
column169: A review of load securement requirements and techniques will be conducted with drivers and shipping personnel. Re-training will be conducted as necessary to ensure compliance with DOT and Clean Harbors regulations and procedures.

At the time of the incident John Adams was driving truck T1004 and acid tube A9005 (West on RT-250 (two-lane/median/two-lane), near the 21 mile marker, 3 miles West of Miller St.  At which point, Car A on the opposing side of the road hit a deer.  The deer then ricocheted and hit Car B who veered over towards John Adam, hitting the driver side dual, assembly knocking of the outer tires (as per Highway Patrol).  The lack of tires caused problems in controlling the vehicle (As per Thomas Stoffer).  The truck veered left, the right, and then hard left at which point the truck rolled 270 degrees, crushing cab.   Also a tire had rolled to east bound lane hitting Car C's passenger side of hood and windshield.  At this point emergency responders were called and dispatched was informed.  As I, James Dobra, arrived on the scene, Firefighters were using Jaws of Life to remove John Adams from the wreckage. When he was removed, he was in a state of cardiac arrest, CPR was performed, and he was move to Twin city hospital then to Akron.  The vehicle had pin hole leak on tank-side of vent valve, 75-gal of acid was lost.
column169: Following incident investigations by multiple agencies, it was determined that our driver did everything in his power to reduce the possibility of loss of life of other individuals involved in the incident.    Action Items that will be reviewed by US Well Services Management for implementation include:    1.  Routes Review - All routes are to be reviewed to determine the safest route; Review will include road conditions, construction, population, wildlife, weather and any other factors that may not be advantageous for the type of vehicle being driven on the route.    2.  Additional training on crash avoidance  3.  Additional training and awareness of wildlife activity in the area    Additional action items may be forthcoming at the completion of the investigation

column168: At 0319 EST, it was reported that a 330 gallon tote was leaking approximately 1-gallon of the liquid to the floor of a trailer at the R&L Carrier facility in Wilmington, OH. The release was the result of a valve leaking near the lid of the tote. The release was immediate. A contractor, Midwest Environmental Services, responded to the site to perform all clean-up activities. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted by the release. The site was returned to prior condition.

At approximately 1800 hours CT on the BNSF Sand Hills Subdivision at Hecla, NE MP 281 a passing train noticed liquid leaking from the top of BNSF tank car BNSF 880631.  The train crew was notified and stopped immediately.  Local mechanical forces responded and found a portion of a gasket along with loose bolts hanging out of the four bolt flange where the liquid valve bolts to the pipe.  BNSF Hazmat responder arrived on scene and was able to fashion a new gasket and secured the valve so the car could be set out and cleaned at the next siding location 3 miles ahead.  The following morning BNSF contractor Haz-Mat Response out of North Platte, NE arrived to clean the shell of the formerly leaking car and four others which were impacted by spray.  They proceeded to remediate the site by using absorbent pads and micro blaze spray on the affected areas of ballast where the leak hit the ground.  Approximate loss of 50 gallons was estimated and was confined to an area between the rails which ran a distance of 400 feet.  No waterways, drains or ditches were impacted.  The car was moved to destination in Alliance, NE for offloading.  Car owner has been notified to apply for OTMA upon empty release.
column169: Review incident with loading facility to ensure they check for obvious signs of deteriorated gaskets and loose bolts on valve assemblies during the loading process.

In the early morning of November 2, 2015, a Dupre Logistics tanker trailer was involved in a multiple vehicle accident that resulted in a rollover and fire. As a direct result of the accident, the tanker caught fire and released all material contents (UN1203 Gasoline) via means of soil absorption or evaporation. No drains or waterways were impacted. The release was immediate. The driver of the vehicle was pronounced deceased by the fire department after an investigation of the scene. No further injuries or fatalities were reported. The fire was extinguished by the Liberty-Eylau Fire Department and an environmental contractor conducted clean-up operations.

column168: On November 30, 2015 at 0515 ET, a 55-gallon steel drum released approximately 1 cup to the drum body due to a defect in the drum bottom rim/seam. No soils, drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted by the release. A cleanup contractor responded and over-packed the drum into an 85-gallon steel salvage drum. The over-pack was staged on site.

On November 30, 2015 at 0500 ET, three 55-gallon poly drums released approximately 1 pint to the top of the drums due to loose bung caps. A cleanup contractor responded and inspected/secured the caps. The drums were decontaminated and the caps were properly tightened down. A slosh test showed that the caps were properly secured. All generated waste was placed into a 5-gallon poly pail for transportation and disposal.

On November 30, 2015 at 0400 ET, a cardboard box containing four 1-gallon poly jugs was pushed off of a skid during fork-lift operations which caused the box to drop to the concrete dock floor and one of the jugs to become compromised. Approximately 1/2 gallon released to the concrete dock floor and the carboard box the jugs were contained in. A cleanup contractor responded to neutralize and clean up the release. The cardboard box containing all four 1-gallon poly jugs and the impacted absorbents were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum for transportation and disposal.

CN transportation department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car RCRX 2194 (Class 8, UN 1789 / Residue Last Contained, HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA. At 0010 EST, a 55-gallon drum was found to be leaking approximately 2 ounces of Phosphric Acid Solution at the terminal location in Greencastle PA. The release was found to be the result of a loose cap that was on the drum and was immediate. A contractor was dispatched to the site to perform mitigation activities, over packing the drum after a cap tightening was unsuccessful. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted by the release. The site was returned to previous conditions.

A BNSF mixed commodity train derailed 13 loaded tank cars of ethanol on main track.  Cause of this derailment is currently under investigation. The bottom outlet secondary flange was reinstalled to mitigate the leak.  TCBX 192552 deemed destroyed and was transloaded. On November 15, 2015 at 1620 Hours personnel in the CSXT West Industrial Park discovered DBUX 302153, a loaded tank car of Isopropanol leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified. Contractor SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve leaking. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contract personnel fixed the problem and cleaned up spill material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     NAR Cause Code: 550 - Bottom Outlet Valve    2 (5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: Driver picked up a shipment of hazardous waste at the generators location and loaded into a box truck.  While having driven a short distance he noticed what appeared to be a cloud coming from the vehicle.  He pulled off the road and noticed liquid coming from under the door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the truck.  The bottom valve of a 275 gallon tote was broken causing the liquid to leak on to the truck floor and onto the gravel surface of the road shoulder.  TX DOT and TCEQ were notified and incident #20154196 was created.  TXDOT and the response crew are working out the details of the road shoulder remediation.
column169: The driver had installed the valve closure that is used by the generator.  This is not the standard closure but one that has a camlock.  This causes the closure to slightly protrude past the outside of the IBC.  The dog ear was found broken on the floor of the truck along with the zip tie.  The leaking tote was loaded with the valve to the right against another tote.  Had the unit been loaded with a board or something to insure against the protruding valve coming in contact with the other tote this may not have leaked.  The driver will be retrained in proper blocking and bracing.

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, a drum was discovered leaking inside the trailer. Further investigation revealed that the drum was punctured by a sharp piece of freight that was loaded in front of it. The drum was immediately placed into an over pack. The absorbent used to clean up released material were also placed in the over pack. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: Placing the proper dunnage around the drums to protect them may have prevented this release. This incident may be used as a learning tool in future dock meetings as an example of the importance of proper freight loading techniques.

column168: A 55 gallon drum was found to be leaking from a worn cap on the drum. The bung cap was found to be stripped and would not hold a seal. The drum was placed into an over pack and returned to the shipper.

The employee concluded his delivery on one side of the building, he secured his hose as normal then he headed to the second set of cages on the opposite side of the building. While driving he had a loud pop sound, when this happened he thought he blew a tire and was getting out to check it. When he moved his truck forward he drove over the hose bursting it and he saw propane coming from under the truck and he immediately did all the emergency procedures and shut everything off in the truck. As soon as that was done all the propane was contained and the only loss of propane was what was in the hose about 4 gallons. We are assuming the Employee stepped on the button on the remote that releases the hose and this is what made the hose come out and the employee did not see it. There were no injuries and no property damage. The hose has been replaced.
column169: Corrective training and verbal counseling were conducted with the employee and will be done also during this months safety meeting.

The failure of the totes' structure led to a rapid time of release.  The release impacted local soils and a nearby creek.  The release was secured with boom, and freestanding product was pumped.  All salvageable material was pumped into a tote.

At approximately 03:20 PM Monday, November 16th   company driver Joseph Heyer was involved in a single vehicle rollover accident.  Driver was transporting Hazardous Waste solid NOS (Lead) from NYCDDC Brooklyn, NY to Clean Earth, Kearny NJ.  He was transporting approx. 22 tons of cargo being shipped on a Hazardous Waste Manifest.  The accident occurred as driver was exiting 95N and entering 15W near the toll plaza.      Mr. Heyer reported he was traveling at approx. 35MPH when he started to sneeze.  He believes he jerked the wheel during the sneezing episode and only recalls becoming alert when the truck came to rest on the passenger side.  Two Horwith drivers were traveling behind the unit at the time of the accident. Louis Vasquez was traveling directly behind unit 245 and driver Christian Smith was following Vasquez.  Both drivers stopped and assisted with the accident.  911 was immediately notified.  Christian Smith assisted to control the scene while Louis Vasquez assisted extracting driver, Joseph Heyer from the overturned unit.  The fuel tank was not ruptured and no other fluid was released.  Approximately 10 ton of the contaminated cargo was released onto the roadway.      Upon hearing of the accident Horwith Implemented our Contingency plan.  Clean Earth was immediately notified of the situation.  NJDEP was also notified (report #151116152120) along with the US National Response Center (report #1133563).  NJ State Police arrived and took command of the scene. Horwith was instructed not to send an Emergency Response Cleanup Team as the state police would handle.  The NJTA responded and initiated all cleanup efforts.  Horwith was asked to have another unit brought to the scene so the product could be remediated and shipped for disposal.  At approximately 5:00 PM the NJTA reloaded the material into unit #243 and Driver John Dubiel transported it to the Cleanearth disposal facility.

column168: On 11/23/15 BNSF Hub personnel reported a clear liquid product leaking from under unit OOLU 850833.  In the interest of safety this unit was moved to the HazMat containment area pending inspection as it leaked approximately one ounce every 5 minutes. Unit leaked approximately 20 ounces of product inside rail car NOKL 210192 prior to it being unloaded, with an additional 10 ounces on the ground trackside.    The product was placarded 1993 Combustible Liquid N.O.S. and was being shipped inside container OOLU 850833 which was riding on freight car NOKL 210192.  One of the seventeen 330 gallon totes was found with the lid over the fill hole unscrewed and laying on top of the tote which allowed liquid to splash out of the tote and onto the container floor and railcar.    Contractor was called and was able to clean all surfaces and re-apply the cap on the tote.  Shipment continued in transit once contractor was finished.  No environmental remediation required.
column169: Ensure proper loading and securement of all hazmat shipments including tote closures.

column25: Tesoro Refining & Marketing Co. (by Crestwood Midstream Partners LF)
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 11/30/15, WA UTC inspector Bob Johnston found the TILX 281849 and TILX 281903 to have minor staining on the top of the car near the manway closure.  Mr. Johnston reported the information to BNSF.  The car was in train U-EPPFTE2-29, arrangements were made to isolate the cars from the train on a repair track for Hazmat contractors to inspect, repair and clean the cars.  The cars were staged on the repair track early on 12/1/15 and the contractor inspected the cars.  The manway closure was secured and had a gasket installed.  It was determined that there was inadequate torque on the manway swing bolts to properly secure the manway lid.  A new manway nozzle gasket was installed, the lid was re-secured and the car was cleaned.  It was estimated that no more than 1 gallon of material had spilled from car based up a visual estimation and that no oil had impacted the ground with only impacts to the shell of the car.
column169: The shipper should review their current securement procedures on cars before offering for transportation.  Specifically, a review of proper manway lid closure procedures including proper torque dependent upon gasket type should be reviewed with loading employees.  The shipper has been notified and provided with details surrounding this release.

column168: On 11/11/15 Terminal Mgr Kevin Roberts was contacted by the CSX Switch Crew stating that CBTX 780830 (located on track 6) had some freezing on dome lid along with a "gas odor".  The TM arrived at the terminal by 23:45 and immediately consulted with the Hillsborough Fire Department (on site).  The TM along with fire rescue used the LPG rack on Track 6 to ascend the car.  He opened the dome lid and discovered that the plugs on the liquid and vapor lines were not too tight.  One of the liquid lines was slightly ajar due to a small amount of trash/debris in the valve not allowing it to seat properly.  The TM tightened the valve and plugs.  The hazmat responders tested the valves with a leak detector and determined that everything was secure with no LPG present.
column169: To prevent future actions:    Entire terminal held a stand down to discuss the importance and methods for securing RCs.    The terminal added a step in the process requiring a supervisor to secure all cars before departing every night.

BY MY OBSERVATION THERE SEEMED NO PROBLEMS WITH THE PACKAGING AND BY MY EXPERIENCE HAD BEEN MOST LIKELY DROPPED WHILE UNLOADING/LOADING.

column168: REPORT FROM DISPATCHER: AT 8:53 PM ON 11-07: DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD CHECKED THE AIR VALVE AND IT WAS HARD TO MOVE SO HE THOUGHT THAT IT WAS CLOSED. GLS HCI LOADS REQUIRE AN INHIBITOR ADDITIVE TO BE LOADED AFTER THE HCL IS LOADED. WHILE REMOVING THE INHIBITOR HOSE FROM THE DOME, THE DRIVER LOST GRIP OF THE HOSE, SPILLING THE INHIBITOR INTO THE CRASH BOX OF THE TRAILER. HE CLOSED THE DOME LID AND RINSED DOWN THE CRASH BOX WITH EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF WATER UNDER THE LOADING RACK. HE THEN DROVE TO THE PVS TECH PLANT TO COMPLETE HIS SCALE TICKET BY SCALING OUT. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT GLS, HE NOTICED LIQUID DRAINING FROM THE AIR CONNECTION AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE TOP AIR VALVE WAS NOT SECURELY CLOSED AND NEITHER WERE THE TWO ADDITIONAL VALVES ON THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. NO INJURIES/EXPOSURE HAS BEEN REPORTED.
column169: AROUND 9:50 PM THE PVS GUARD ON DUTY CONTACTED A MAINTENANCE OPERATOR TO INFORM HIM THAT THE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED THROUGH THE PVS TECH PLANT AND DOWN THE DRIVEWAY. MAINTENANCE ARRIVED TO FIND THAT THE DRIVER WAS AT THE PVS TRANS TERMINAL CLEANING UP THE MATERIAL THAT HAD SPRAYED THROUGH THE PLANT. HE PROCEEDED TO PVS TEACH TO CLEAN UP THE DRIVEWAY AND MATERIAL SPILLED IN THE PLANT.     CAUSAL FACTOR: PERSONNEL DIFFICULTY, EQUIPMENT DIFFICULTY  ROOT CAUSE: PROCEDURES, EQUIPMENT RELIABILITY, TRAINING.   NEAR ROOT CAUSE: PROCEDURE NOT USED, TRAINING NI, OVERALL PROGRAM  ROOT CAUSE: PROCEDURE NOT SUED, ON-THE-JOB TRAINING NI, PROCEDURE FOR DETERMINING NEEDS OF EQUIPMENT.     CONTRIBUTING FACTORS:  VALVE WAS HARD TO OPERATE  NO REAL FAMILIAR WITH CUSTOMER   HEAVY WORK LOAD.

column168: 1. DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT PONY MOTOR HAD SHORTED OUT AND PUMP WAS NOT WORKING, WHILE IN ROUTE (TANK 3208)  2. IT WAS DECIDED TO USE ANOTHER TANKER(3312)AND THEN TRANSFER LOAD TO THE DAMAGE TANKER TO BRING THE LOAD BACK FOR DISPOSAL AND THEN TO TERMINAL FOR REPAIRS   3. WHILE TRANSFERRING LOAD FROM 3312 TO 3208, THE FLOAT VALVE GOT STUCK AND DRIVER DID NOT REALIZE THAT HE WAS NOT BUILDING VACUUM NEEDED TO CLEAR HOSES AFTER TRANSFER. WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE HOSES, INSTEAD OF HAVING VACUUM HE HAD PRESSURE AND IT BLEW MATERIAL AND AIR IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  4. ABSORBENT PADS AND DRY SORB WAS IMMEDIATELY PUT DOWN TO MINIMIZE RELEASE, AND TO PROTECT THE STORM DRAIN FROM MATERIAL.  5. A SECOND RELEASE OCCURRED AND THIS TIME MATERIAL DID GET INTO STORM DRAIN.  6. A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN AND THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED, AND STORM DRAIN WAS CLEANED OUT, NO MATERIAL LEFT THE PROPERTY.
column169: BECAUSE OF THE JOB SCOPE CHANGE, IN THE FUTURE A JSA WILL BE PERFORMED ANYTIME THE NORMAL SCOPE OF WORK CHANGES. A NEW JSA WAS PUT TOGETHER FOR THIS TYPE OF WORK FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT. TRAINING FOR DRIVERS TO INSPECT AND BECOME MORE FAMILIAR WITH THE EQUIP THEY ARE OPERATING PRIOR TO THAT EQUIPMENTS USE .LOWERING OF TANK GAUGES TO THE FENDER LEVEL INSTEAD OF ON TOP OF THE TANK, SO THAT DRIVERS CAN READ THEM EASIER.

column168: Driver arrived at customer, he had just started offloading the product Fluorosilicic Acid. He had just started when he realized his actuator was not working correctly, it was stripped. There were approximately 3gallqns spilled out on asphalt. He had all his protective gear on so he did not get any product on himself. He cleaned it up. There was one employee there that assisted him in clean up. They did clean up with water hose, they put fluorite through the water to wash it all off asphalt. Event 48759

column168: A single 55-gallon steel drum of paint was punctured by a forklift operator during dock operations. The release was contained to the dock floor. The release was accidental and immediate. column168: RAIL CAR CCBX 3590 CONTAINING A LOAD OF UN 1992, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, 6.1,111, WAS FOUND WITH PRODUCT VENTING FROM A FAULTY RELIEF VALVE- THE TOP FROM A VALVE THAT WAS LOOSE. A LOCAL COMPANY THAT HAS A HM TEAM WAS CALLED AND THEY RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THE LOCAL MUNICIPALITIES WERE CONTACTED AND THEY CLOSED HWY. 69 AROUND THE AREA OF THE TANK CAR FOR ABOUT AN HOUR UNTIL IT WAS KNOWN TO BE SAFE TO OPEN TO THE PUBLIC. THE CAR SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY CHEM-TREK AND THEY IMMEDIATELY SENT A CREW TO THE SITE AND REPAIRED THE VALVE TO STOP THE VENTING BY THE PRESSURIZED CAR. THE CAR VENTED FOR APPROX. 5.5 HOURS UNTIL REPAIRED. THIS CAR WAS LOADED AND SECURED BY 3RD PARTY COMPANY SGS PETROLEUM SERVICES TAFT, LA SITE. POC. column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: Shipment was tendered to Nippon Cargo Airlines in Tokyo, Japan on 18Nov15. Shipment was tendered to NCA in Tokyo as general cargo and handled as such. Cargo arrived in Chicago on flight KZ160/18Nov15. Shipment was delivered without irregularity on 19Nov15 to Yusen Air & Sea. On 05Jan16, it was reported to us in Chicago by NCA headquarters in Tokyo that the shipment consisted of helicopter parts that should have been tendered to us by the shipper as a dangerous goods shipment under UN3363. This information was reported to NCA in Tokyo by the shipper, Yusen Air & Sea, on 05Jan16. This report is the immediate result of this informatined leared today.
column169: NCA staff system wide goes through dangerous goods training to help identify undeclared dangerous goods. This is part of the IATA DG training that all NCA staff handlign DG's go through. In this case, there was no marking on the cargo or indication on the documents that would have essentially raised a red flag to our staff during acceptance in Tokyo, handling and delivery to the customer in Chicago.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: UNIVAR DRIVER PULLED UP TO SAN JOSE STATE UNIVERSITY TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF SULFURIC ACID. THE DRIVER WAS ON THE DECK OF THE TRAILER TENDING TO THE LOAD AND INADVERTENTLY STEPPED ON THE HOSE CONNECTED TO THE TANK. THE HOSE BROKE OFF WHICH CAUSED LEAKAGE FROM THE PUMP. APPROXIMATELY 0.57 LITERS DRIPPED TO THE PAVEMENT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND A YARD TECHNICIAN WAS DISPATCHED TO REPAIR THE PUMP AND HELP CLEAN UP THE SPILL. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS SPREAD OVER THE SULFURIC TO NEUTRALIZE IT. THE WASTE WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON BUCKET WITH LID AND BROUGHT BACK TO UNIVAR FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: DRIVER WILL UNDERGO SAFETY AWARENESS REFRESHER TRAINING TO HEIGHTEN THIS AWARENESS OF THIS SURROUNDINGS.   THE UNLOADING PROCESS WILL BE EVACUATED TO QUALIFY THE CURRENT PROCEDURE. AMENDMENTS AND UPDATES WILL BE ADDED AS NECESSARY TO IMPROVE THE PROCESS.  THE SETUP OF THE EQUIPMENT WILL BE ANALYZED TO ASSES IF THERE ARE ANY OPPORTUNITIES TO MODIFY THE EQUIPMENT TO MAKE IT A SAFER WORK ENVIRONMENT.

column168: CANADIAN PACIFIC TRAIN TRAVELING THROUGH WATERTOWN WL DERAILED AT THE CP/UP DIAMOND IN WITHIN THE CITY LIMITS OF WATERTOWN. THE CAR WAS DAMAGED AND PUNCTURED. column168: Shipment traveled from Germantown, Wl to San Diego, CA on FedEx Freight. The bill of lading provided to FedEx Freight states the cargo was 10 cartons of epoxy resin on one pallet. The cargo arrived at FedEx Trade Networks in San Diego, CA. FedEx Trade Networks was to forward the shipment on another truck to Ensenada, Mexico. FedEx Trade Networks employees reviewing the packing lists and other documents for customs clearance preparation noted the commodities on the packing list did not match the inbound bill of lading. FedEx Trade. Networks employees noted what appears to be removal of hazard class labels from the fiberboard boxes. They stopped the shipment until the actual commodities inside the cartons could be determined. Based on items detailed on the enclosed packing lists, FedEx Trade Networks employees obtained Safety Data Sheets (SDS)from manufacturer websites. Packages were opened to verify contents matched the packing lists. Actual contents verified by physical inventory and verifying against chemical manufacturer SDS:5 cartons with (4) 5 liter metal jerricans of 1B73-5L (HumiSeal 1B73) which according to HumiSeal SDS is UN1263,Paint, 3, PGM ///1 carton with (1) 5 liter metal jerrican of T73-5L (HumiSeal Thinner T73) which according to HumiSeal SDS is UN1263, Paint Related Material, 3, PGII ///1 carton with (1)5 liter metal jerrican of.T73-5L, 50bags of Urabond 24N 50 mL, and 5 Loctite E-120HP epoxy injection at 50 ml_. According to Urabond SDS, 24N isUN2206, Isocyanates, Toxic, N.O.S. (dicyclohexyl methane diisocyanate), 6.1, PG II. According to Henkel SDS,Loctite E-120HP is not regulated by ground. /// 3 cartons with 100 bags of Urabond 24N 50 ml.SDS and photographs attached.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO MARION COUNTY LANDFILL, OCALA FL FOR A FUEL DELIVERY ON NOVEMBER 3, 2015. WHEN THE DRIVER GOT THE LOCATION, HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS NO WAY TO STICK THE TANKS TO SEE HOW MUCH FUEL WAS IN THE TANK. THE DRIVER ASKED A WORKER AT THE LOCATION IF THERE WAS A VEEDER-ROOT READING ON THE VOLUME OF FUEL IN THE TANKS. THE WORKERS STATED THAT HE DID NOT KNOW BUT IF THEY ORDERED THE LOAD IT WILL FILL. AFTER 15 MINUTES OF PUMPING INTO THE TANK, THE DRIVER NOTICED DIESEL FUEL COMING OUT OF THE EMERGENCY RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND STARTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH SPILL PADS. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED ON THE GROUND.
column169: B-LINE CARRIERS POLICY ON DELIVERING FUEL:  NO DRIVER SHALL DROP OR PUMP THEIR PRODUCT INTO A TANK UNLESS THE DRIVER IS 100 PERCENT CERTAIN THAT THE LOAD WILL FIT. THIS POLICY WILL BE EXPLAINED AT DRIVERS ORIENTATION AND AT THE NEXT TRAINING MEETING SCHEDULED FOR JANUARY 27, 2016.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 23, 2015 EXPEDITORS-SLC RECEIVED A REQUEST TO PICK UP 13 PALLETS OF COMMODITY DESCRIBED AS CLEANING COMPOUNDS AND PLASTIC COMPONENTS PACKED IN DRUMS ("THE SHIPMENT") FROM SHIPPER MELALEUCA, INC. ("THE SHIPPER") FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION SERVICES TO SHANGHAI, CHINA. THE COMMERCIAL INVOICE RECEIVED WITH THE CARGO DESCRIBED THE SHIPMENT AS CONTAINING "NO DANGEROUS GOODS" (EXHIBIT A).     UPON PHYSICALLY RECEIVING THE CARGO IN THE EXPEDITORS-SLC WAREHOUSE ON NOVEMBER, 2015, AN EXPEDITORS- SLC EMPLOYEE NOTED THAT 4 OF THE DRUMS WERE MARKED AS UN3082 (EXHIBIT B). THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED ON HOLD AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY EXPEDITORS-SLC FOR CLARIFICATION REGARDING THE MATERIALS RECEIVED.     ON NOVEMBER 25, 2015, THE SHIPPER PROVIDED EXPEDITORS-SLC WITH WRITTEN EXPLANATION (RECEIVED FROM THE VENDOR OF THE MATERIALS) AS WELL AS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET CONFIRMING THAT THE MATERIALS INSIDE OF THE DRUMS ARE CLASSIFIED AS UN3082 UNDER THE GLOBALLY HARMONIZED SYSTEM OF CLASSIFICATION AND LABELING OF CHEMICALS ("GHS") USED BY THE INTERNATIONAL CIVIL AVIATION ORGANIZATION'S TECHNICAL INSTRUCTIONS ("ICAO TI") (EXHIBIT C).    THE DRUMS LABELED UN 3082 WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER TO BE BROUGHT INTO CONFORMANCE WITH THE ICAO TI ON DECEMBER 2, 2015.
column169: IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE DISCOVERY OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS, THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR AN ACCOUNT OF THE EVENTS. EXPEDITORS-SLC'S DISTRICT MANAGER AND DISTRICT TRADE COMPLIANCE MANAGER HAD A TELEPHONE CONVERSATION WITH THE SHIPPER'S SENIOR LOGISTICS MANAGER TO DISCUSS MEASURES TO PREVENT RE-OCCURRENCE. SUBSEQUENT TO THIS CALL, EXPEDITORS-SLC RECEIVED THE ATTACHED LETTER OF EXPLANATION (EXHIBIT D) ON THIS INCIDENT FROM THE SHIPPER.    EXPEDITORS HAS A VERY ROBUST COMPLIANCE PROGRAM. AS PART OF OUR PROGRAM, ALL EMPLOYEES GLOBALLY ARE REQUIRED TO TAKE GENERAL DG AWARENESS TRAINING ANNUALLY. IN THIS CIRCUMSTANCE, EXPEDITORS-SLC'S AIRPORT EXPORT OPERATIONS STAFF DISCOVERED THE DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGE THAT WAS UNDECLARED TO EXPEDITORS-SLC AS DANGEROUS GOODS AND TOOK APPROPRIATE MEASURES TO ENSURE THAT DANGEROUS GOODS PACKAGED TENDERED FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION ARE BROUGHT INTO CONFORMANCE PRIOR TO OFFERING TO AN AIR CARRIER AND DULY REPORTED AS REQUIRED BY 49 C.F.R.171.16.

column43: FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION DWG DRINKING WATER GRADE
column168: PVS TRANSPORTATION EQUIPMENT DID NOT FAIL. BASED ON PVST DRIVER ACCOUNT THE TANK WAS OBSERVED OVERFLOWING BY A MASSILLON WTP EMPLOYEE, AT WHICH TIME THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE TRANSFER PROCESS. AT THAT TIME THE MATERIAL WAS ESCAPING FROM THE TANK THROUGH THE 3" OVERFILL LINE RUNNING THE HEIGHT OF THE TANK. PVST DRIVER INDICATED THAT HE WAS ALSO PRESENT TO SEE THE START OF THE RELEASE FROM THE TANK AND HE IMMEDIATELY WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK TO SHUT DOWN. JOHN STATED THAT AT THAT TIME A MASSILLON EMPLOYEE EXITED THE PLANT AND SHOUTED THAT THE TANK WAS "ABOUT TO BLOW". AT JUST ABOUT THAT TIME THE TANK DID FAIL, MANIFESTING A CRACK ABOUT 3/4 OF THE WAY AROUND THE TANK CIRCUMFERENCE AND ABOUT 2' FROM THE TOP OR THE TANK, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE. MASSILLON WTP EMPLOYEES RINSED THE RELEASED MATERIAL TO FACILITY TREATMENT SYSTEM. PVST DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLEAR HIS PRODUCT TRANSFER LINES WITHOUT INCIDENT OR FURTHER RELEASE AND LEFT THE SITE AT 2:55 P.M.
column169: IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SIGHT GAUGE ON THE CUSTOMER TANK WAS NON-FUNCTIONAL AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY. CUSTOMER ASSERTS THAT THERE WERE NO OTHER MATERIALS STORED IN THE TANK DURING THE APPROXIMATELY 5 MONTH GAP BETWEEN DELIVERIES OF PVS TECHNOLOGIES DWG FERRIC CHLORIDE. CUSTOMER REPORTS THAT THEIR TANK "IMPLODED", BUT PVS IS UNABLE TO DETERMINE WITH REASONABLE CERTAINTY HOW THAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN CAUSED WHILE ADDING PRODUCT TO THE TANK. ONE THEORY IS THAT MORE MATERIAL WAS BEING DRAWN FROM THE TANK THAN WAS ENTERING IT WHILE BEING FILLED, BUT THE CUSTOMER ASSERTED THAT THE ONLY ACTIVITY ON THE TANK WAS A 10 GPH FEED PUMP WHICH WAS OPERATING AT THE TIME FOR THEIR PROCESSING. ANOTHER THEORY IS THAT, SINCE FIBERGLASS TANKS OF THIS TYPE ARE TYPICALLY MUCH THINNER TOWARD THE TOP OF THE TANK, THE COLUMN OF FECI ESCAPING THROUGH THE TANK OVERFILL LINE COULD HAVE CREATED SUFFICIENT VACUUM TO COLLAPSE THE TANK. CUSTOMER HAS NOT DISCLOSED THE COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE LOSS OF THE STORAGE TANK OR THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS. BASED ON THE 20 GALLON VOLUME OF PVS TECHNOLOGIES DWG FERRIC CHLORIDE RELEASED AND THE FACT THAT MASSILLON WTP EMPLOYEES RINSED THE MATERIAL TO THEIR IN-HOUSE TREATMENT SYSTEM, PVS IS UNABLE TO COMPLETE THE DAMAGES SECTION OF THIS REPORT.

column168: ON 11/28/2015 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00AM, SEMI-TRUCK HAULING TWO TANKERS FILLED WITH CRUDE OIL CRUSHED IN PROVO CANYON. THE SEMI WAS DRIVING WEST HEAR MILE POST 13 DURING INCLEMENT WEATHER WITH SNOW AND A TEMPERATURE OF APPROXIMATELY 25 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A LANE CHANGE TO PROVIDE ROOM FOR A VEHICLE ON THE SHOULDER WHEN HE HIT A PATCH OF SLUSH. HE LOST OF CONTROL THE SEMI, WHICH VEERED LEFT AND CRASHED INTO THE MEDIAN BARRIER. BOTH THE CAB AND TRAILERS ROLLED OVER. THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ACROSS ALL EASTBOUND AND WESTBOUND LANES. THE FRONT TANK, HOLDING APPROXIMATELY 4,500 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL, RUPTURED AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 83 BARRELS OF ITS CONTENTS. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED, AS WELL AS THE NRC AND STATE OF UTAH. CLEANUP CONTRACTORS WERE IMMEDIATELY MOBILIZED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.     CRUDE OIL SPILLED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT WAS RECOVERED. ALL IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATIONS.
column169: SAVAGE HAS INSTITUTED A DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM FOR ALL EMPLOYEES, INCLUDING CDL DRIVERS. SAVAGE HAS ALSO INFORMED DRIVERS ABOUT OPERATING IN INCIDENT WEATHER, AND REINFORCING THAT THEY HAVE THE AUTHORITY TO STOP WORK WHEN CIRCUMSTANCES (E.G. WEATHER, EQUIPMENT CONDITION, ETC.) WARRANT SUCH ACTION.
